      Some GameStop anniversary content I guess
   =20
 =20
This week is the one-year anniversary of  the GameStop=C2=A0thing.=C2=A0Fro=
m Monday, Jan. 25, 2021, through Friday, Jan. 29, 2021, GameStop Corp.=E2=
=80=99s stock traded as low as $61.13 per share and as high as $483; it end=
ed the week at $197.44, up 204% from the previous week=E2=80=99s close. Tra=
ding in the stock was halted for volatility 37 times during that week, plus=
 Robinhood Markets Inc. and some other brokers briefly  restricted customer=
s from buying it due to  clearinghouse margin troubles. By mid-February the=
re were at least seven movies and television shows about GameStop in the wo=
rks. Everyone=E2=80=99s brain broke that week and stayed broken. More meme =
stocks followed. Elon Musk made Dogecoin into a meme. Donald Trump did a me=
me stock. Everything was like this. It was  the year of the meme stock. Tha=
t is, 2021 was the year of the meme stock.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CI will see you bac=
k here in 2022,=E2=80=9D  I wrote, in my last column of 2021,=C2=A0=E2=80=
=9Cwhen everything will be absolutely normal.=E2=80=9DI don=E2=80=99t want =
to say that that was=C2=A0right =E2=80=94=C2=A0honestly I was kidding =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0but I do feel a little bit like people are celebrating the anni=
versary of the meme stock boom by declaring that it=E2=80=99s over? For ins=
tance, here is a Wall Street Journal article about WallStreetBets, the Redd=
it forum that ignited the GameStop boom and became the center of the meme-s=
tock world for a while:These days, some one-time fans say it is hardly wort=
h clicking on.Those who once scoured the online message forum for brazen an=
d unexpected trading ideas say they are mostly finding members still chatti=
ng about stocks such as GameStop Corp. and AMC Entertainment Holdings Inc.=
=C2=A0 Constructive feedback on trades, some users complain, has largely be=
en replaced by cheerleading. Devotees who were once glued to the forum=E2=
=80=94watching power users like Keith Gill, or =E2=80=9CDeepF=E2=80=94ingVa=
lue,=E2=80=9D post bold bets on GameStop=E2=80=94say they have largely aban=
doned the page in favor of other trading communities.And in this morning=E2=
=80=99s =E2=80=9C5 Things to Start Your Day=E2=80=9D Bloomberg newsletter, =
Joe Weisenthal writes that a lot of the memeiest and most retail-driven par=
ts of the market have actually been underperforming since last February,=C2=
=A0=E2=80=9Cthe retail crowd has been badly lagging the S&P 500 for a while=
 now,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cthe whole =E2=80=98Reddit vs. Hedge Funds=E2=80=
=99 meme that came out of the GameStop story really did turn out to be the =
peak of the mania.=E2=80=9DMeanwhile the broad stock market got crushed all=
 last week and is down more today. The S&P 500 index is now in what people =
like to call a =E2=80=9Ccorrection,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0a drop of 10% from the mo=
st recent high, which in this case is Jan. 3. I have always thought this wa=
s sort of=C2=A0a dumb euphemism but now, I mean, I guess I see the point.Lo=
ng before GameStop, in April 2020, I coined what I have called  the Boredom=
 Market Hypothesis:The theory is something like: Retail investors are not t=
rading=C2=A0because they have an informational advantage and a reasonable e=
xpectation of profit.=C2=A0They are trading because it is fun, or because i=
t looks fun. They see people making money in the stock market, it looks fun=
 and easy to make money in the stock market, they start trading stocks. As =
long as it is fun=E2=80=94as long as stocks go up=E2=80=94they increase the=
ir investments. When it stops being fun=E2=80=94when stocks go down=E2=80=
=94they get out.The weird thing about the coronavirus crisis is that it sim=
ultaneously (1) caused a stock market crash and (2) eliminated most=C2=A0fo=
rms of fun.When the world shut down in the spring of 2020, people turned to=
 day-trading stocks because, even though the market=C2=A0had just crashed, =
trading stocks was still more fun than their other entertainment options. A=
nd then trading stocks became, improbably, really fun, a source of social c=
onnection and populist excitement, and also those stocks went up a lot whic=
h was fun. In 2022, there are more fun things to do, and frantic day tradin=
g is less fun than it used=C2=A0to be. It has gotten old; the message board=
s are not alive with excitement but are just playing the hits. Also the mar=
ket is crashing again! Where is the fun in that?Meanwhile at noon today Gam=
eStop was trading above $88 per share. When I first wrote about GameStop, w=
hen everything went utterly insane, when GameStop=E2=80=99s soaring price s=
eemed to make no sense at all, it closed at $76.79. Perhaps we=E2=80=99ll t=
est that today. Or perhaps GameStop used its meme status to successfully  t=
ransform its business; perhaps=C2=A0the magic doesn=E2=80=99t work anymore,=
 but its effects on GameStop have lasted.
