<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Robinhood IPOs</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A simple model of initial public offer=
ings is that on the day of the IPO, a company sells stock for $100 per shar=
e to a selected group of institutional investors, and the next day, the sto=
ck opens for trading and those institutional investors turn around and sell=
 the stock for $150 to any retail investor on Robinhood who wants to buy it=
. This is called the =E2=80=9CIPO pop=E2=80=9D: There is more demand for th=
e stock than is satisfied in the IPO process, so when it opens for trading =
the stock goes up. This model is oversimplified in various important ways b=
ut it has its uses.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If that is your m=
odel it creates an interesting marketing opportunity for Robinhood Markets =
Inc. The pitch goes like this:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; pa=
dding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Go =
to<em>=C2=A0issuers</em>=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0companies thinking about going=
 public =E2=80=94=C2=A0and say, look, if you sell stock in a regular IPO to=
 institutional investors, you will sell your stock at $100 per share and th=
e next day it will pop=C2=A0by 50% as the institutional investors turn arou=
nd and sell it to Robinhood customers at $150. You will have =E2=80=9C<a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26470748.263630/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDEtMDcvdGhlLWlwby=
1tYXJrZXQtd2FzLXRvby1nb29kP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMjQyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpd=
W09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDEyNCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFp=
Z249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5f48a66a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">left money on=
 the table</a>,=E2=80=9D and your=C2=A0venture capitalists will complain. I=
nstead, you should just=C2=A0<em>sell the stock to Robinhood customers your=
self</em>, at $150 per share, avoiding the pop and raising more money for y=
ourself.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Go to=C2=A0<em>customers=
=C2=A0</em>=E2=80=94=C2=A0individual retail investors on Robinhood =E2=80=
=94 and say, look, so much of the money that gets made in stock markets com=
es from buying IPOs at the IPO price. Institutional investors get to buy IP=
O stock at $100 and then it pops to $150 the next day for a quick easy prof=
it. We are going to democratize this process by letting=C2=A0<em>you=C2=A0<=
/em>buy stock at the IPO price and participate in the pop yourself.</li>=09=
<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The issuers sign up to sell, the customer=
s sign up to buy, and now Robinhood is in the IPO underwriting business.</l=
i></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Do you see the problem here? I am being=
 too cute =E2=80=94=C2=A0those numbers ($100 and $150) are not known in adv=
ance, there are lots of other factors beyond selling to retail, etc. =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0but not=C2=A0<em>much=C2=A0</em>too cute. If the IPO pop comes fro=
m Robinhood customers crowding into a stock the day after its IPO, then let=
ting Robinhood customers crowd into the stock the day=C2=A0<em>of</em>=C2=
=A0its IPO doesn=E2=80=99t exactly let them participate in the pop. It just=
 raises the IPO price. Which is what the issuers want, but not necessarily =
what the=C2=A0customers want.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway Robinh=
ood really did launch an =E2=80=9CIPO Access=E2=80=9D program last year whe=
re it got issuers to allocate some IPO shares to its customers=C2=A0and got=
 its customers to buy those shares. We have talked about it =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
along the lines of this model =E2=80=94=C2=A0a <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26470748.263630/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLm=
NvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDUtMjQvbWVycmlsbC1seW5jaC1wdXRzLWRvd24td=
GhlLXBob25lP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMjQyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRt=
X3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDEyNCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHV=
